## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `SerializerTests.cs`

**Summary: 5 Critical · 0 High · 1 Medium · 1 Low**

These tests are in poor shape. Five of eight tests contain tautological or self-referential assertions that will pass regardless of whether the production code is correct. They inflate coverage without verifying behavior.

---

### Critical Findings

---

**① Self-referential assertion — `NormalizeName_AlreadyNormalized_NoChange` (line 37–42)**

The input `"alice"` is *already* lowercase and trimmed. `NameNormalizer.Normalize` calls `.Trim().ToLowerInvariant()`, which is a no-op on this input. The test asserts `input == result`, which is trivially true. It never verifies that normalization actually transforms anything.

```csharp
// BEFORE — tautological: input is already normalized
var name = "alice";
var result = NameNormalizer.Normalize(name);
Assert.AreEqual(name, result);

// AFTER — test the actual transformation
var result = NameNormalizer.Normalize("  ALICE  ");
Assert.AreEqual("alice", result);
```

---

**② Self-referential assertion — `GetDisplayName_ReturnsFormattedName` (line 56–61)**

`GetDisplayName()` returns `Name` verbatim. The test asserts `user.Name == display`, which is `Name == Name` — always true. The test name claims "ReturnsFormattedName" but no formatting is tested. If someone later adds formatting logic, this test won't catch regressions.

```csharp
// BEFORE — asserts a field against itself
Assert.AreEqual(user.Name, display);

// AFTER — assert against a known expected literal
var user = new UserDto { Name = "Alice", Age = 30 };
var display = user.GetDisplayName();
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", display);
```

---

**③ Self-referential assertion — `UpperCase_ToUpper_Works` (line 72–77)**

Input is `"HELLO"` — already uppercase. `.ToUpper()` is a no-op, so `Assert.AreEqual(input, result)` is trivially true. Additionally, this tests `string.ToUpper()` (a BCL method), not any production code in the `Serialization` namespace. It adds nothing.

```csharp
// BEFORE — no-op on already-uppercase input, tests BCL not production code
var input = "HELLO";
var result = input.ToUpper();
Assert.AreEqual(input, result);

// FIX — delete this test entirely. If ToUpper behavior matters in
// production code, test that production method with a lowercase input:
//   var result = "hello".ToUpper();
//   Assert.AreEqual("HELLO", result);
```

---

**④ Self-referential assertion — `Validate_ValidInput_ReturnsSameInput` (line 64–69)**

`Validator.ValidateEmail` returns its input unchanged on success. Asserting `input == result` is trivially true for any valid email. The test provides zero confidence because it never tests the *validation* — i.e., that invalid emails throw.

```csharp
// BEFORE — only tests the pass-through, never the validation
var input = "hello@world.com";
var result = Validator.ValidateEmail(input);
Assert.AreEqual(input, result);

// AFTER — keep the happy-path test, but add the critical rejection test
[TestMethod]
public void ValidateEmail_InvalidInput_Throws()
{
    Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentException>(
        () => Validator.ValidateEmail("not-an-email"));
}
```

---

**⑤ Lossy round-trip assertion — `MapToDto_MapBack_RoundTrip` (line 45–53)**

The production code is *lossy*: `Mapper.ToDto` drops `Id` and `Email` (sets `Age = 0`), and `Mapper.ToEntity` drops `Age` (sets `Id = 0`, `Email = ""`). A round-trip starting from `{ Id=1, Email="a@b.com" }` produces `{ Id=0, Email="" }`. The assertions on line 50 and 52 (`entity.Id == backToEntity.Id`, `entity.Email == backToEntity.Email`) **should fail** (`1 ≠ 0`, `"a@b.com" ≠ ""`). If these tests are reported as passing, something is masking the failure. Either way, a round-trip test on a lossy transformation is fundamentally wrong.

```csharp
// FIX — test each mapping direction independently with known expected values
[TestMethod]
public void MapToDto_MapsFieldsCorrectly()
{
    var entity = new UserEntity { Id = 1, FullName = "Alice Smith", Email = "a@b.com" };
    var dto = Mapper.ToDto(entity);
    Assert.AreEqual("Alice Smith", dto.Name);
    Assert.AreEqual(0, dto.Age); // Age is not mapped — make this explicit
}

[TestMethod]
public void MapToEntity_MapsFieldsCorrectly()
{
    var dto = new UserDto { Name = "Alice Smith", Age = 30 };
    var entity = Mapper.ToEntity(dto);
    Assert.AreEqual("Alice Smith", entity.FullName);
    Assert.AreEqual(0, entity.Id);    // Id is not mapped
    Assert.AreEqual("", entity.Email); // Email is not mapped
}
```

---

### Medium Finding

**⑥ Missing identity check — `Clone_ProducesEqualObject` (line 28–34)**

The test verifies field equality but never asserts that the clone is a *different object*. If `Clone()` returned `this`, the test would still pass.

```csharp
// ADD after existing assertions:
Assert.AreNotSame(original, clone);
```

---

